{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563979"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:08:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:08:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16924"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16924"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.07,0.07,0.63,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67747"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9614"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16924"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53212"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4639"},{"type":"tags","id":"4772"},{"type":"tags","id":"4773"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22693"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67747"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of a painless genital ulcer. She reports unprotected sexual intercourse with a new partner two weeks ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications except for the combined oral contraceptive pill.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a single, well-circumscribed, non-tender ulcer with a firm base on her right labia majora. The inguinal lymph nodes are slightly enlarged but non-tender.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate to confirm diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dark field microscopy","Rapid plasma reagin test alone","Ulcer PCR alone","Ulcer PCR with rapid plasma reagin test","Ulcer culture with rapid plasma reagin test"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features highly suggestive of primary syphilis, characterised by a painless, indurated chancre at the site of inoculation, typically appearing 2-3 weeks after exposure to \u003Cem\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/em\u003E. The presence of non-tender regional lymphadenopathy is also characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlcer PCR with rapid plasma reagin test\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate diagnostic approach. PCR testing of ulcer swabs has largely replaced dark field microscopy as the preferred diagnostic test for primary syphilis due to its high sensitivity and wider availability. Since serological tests may be negative in early infection, both tests should be performed initially, with repeat serology after 2-4 weeks if negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDark field microscopy\u003C/strong\u003E was historically the gold standard for diagnosing primary syphilis but requires specialised equipment and expertise, making it less practical in most clinical settings. PCR testing is now preferred due to its greater accessibility and reliability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid plasma reagin test alone\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient as it may be negative in early primary syphilis due to the serological window period, which can last 1-4 weeks after the appearance of the chancre.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlcer PCR alone\u003C/strong\u003E, while highly sensitive, should be accompanied by serology to establish baseline serological status and aid in monitoring treatment response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlcer culture with rapid plasma reagin test\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as \u003Cem\u003ET. pallidum\u003C/em\u003E cannot be cultured in artificial media. PCR testing is the preferred method for direct detection of the organism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary syphilis classically presents with a painless, indurated chancre at the site of inoculation.","PCR testing of ulcer swabs is now the preferred diagnostic test for primary syphilis as it is more sensitive and widely available than dark field microscopy.","If initial serology is negative, repeat testing after 2-4 weeks is essential as seroconversion may be delayed in early infection."],"references":["Australasian Sexual and Reproductive Health Alliance. Syphilis [Internet]. Sydney (NSW): Australasian STI Management Guidelines; [cited 2024 Dec 6]. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/syphilis/#:~:text=Diagnosis%20is%20by%20a%20combination,2%20weeks%20following%20presumptive%20treatment."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53212"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16924"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53212"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-06T18:49:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-06T18:50:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9614"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67747"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":n